data.title: Dire Straits Essentials
data.description: Formed in Newcastle, England in 1977, Dire Straits was a rock band made up of Mark Knopfler, his younger brother David, John Illsley, and Pick Withers. The group first broke through in 1980 with the instant-classic "Sultans Of Swing". They released four successful albums between 1978 and 1982, but their crowning achievement came in 1985 with the release of Brothers In Arms. The album was popularized by MTV with their video for "Money For Nothing," and became the first album to sell over a million copies on the CD format. Brothers in Arms remains one of the top 10 best-selling albums in the U.K. and has been platinum certified nine time over in the U.S. - over 30 million copies have been sold in total. Despite earning superstar status, the band broke up after a massive international tour - with the exception of a brief reunion that produced the 1991 album 'On Every Street'. (Photo: Rovi)

data.title: Bruce Springsteen Essentials
data.description: Since emerging as a promising post-Dylan singer-songwriter in the mid-’70s, Bruce Springsteen (Long Branch, New Jersey in 1949), has lived up to his nickname — “The Boss” — as perhaps the world’s foremost rock ’n’ roll ambassador. It’s a position he has retained by holding firm in his love for early rock, the British Invasion, classic soul and R&B and folksongs — the signal sounds of American bar music, in other words — and by positioning himself as a kind of interpreter for the working class, the everyman. His songs often tell the stories of those who have fallen off but continue fighting for the broken promises of the American Dream. Though his breakthrough as an American icon began with ‘Born to Run’ (1975), his run of eight LPs from his 1973 debut, ‘Greetings From Asbury Park, N.J.’ through 1987’s ‘Tunnel of Love’ is generally considered one of the most brilliant hot streaks in all of popular music. Today, he continues to record and perform his legendary sweat-soaked marathon concerts. (Photo: Sony)

data.title: Pixies Essentials
data.description: Pixies started in Boston in 1986, and immediately stood out on the alternative rock charts. Surfer Rosa (1988) and Doolittle (1989) are among the most influential albums in the last 25 years, and had a direct influence of indie/alternative rock explosion of the ‘90s and beyond. Bands like Nirvana, Weezer, Pavement and Modest Mouse are all children of the Pixies' distinctive style. Their roots can be traced to Iggy Pop and Captain Beefheart, post-punk (Wire, Pere Ubu), noise rock (Sonic Youth, Hüsker Dü) and power pop (Big Star, Cheap Trick). With an endless punk energy, Pixies mixed those influences into a deliciously strong cocktail all their own, which rarely fell into the mainstream. Marked by only limited success, the band released only four albums during their initial career. After a long breakup, they first reunited briefly in 2003. Following the success of the Doolittle 20th anniversary tour in 2010, and having found a new generation of fans, the band reunited more permanently and, despite the departure of bassist Kim Deal, have begun releasing new material again. (Photo: Rovi)

data.title: The National Essentials
data.description: While indie-rock stalwarts the National emerged from Brooklyn in the early 2000s amid a garage-rock revival that included bands like the Strokes, the Walkmen and, in the U.K., the Libertines, they distinguished themselves by drawing from a wider set of influences. Merging elements of alternative country-rock, Americana and chamber pop as well as post-punk into their moody, crafted indie rock, their earliest albums won a dedicated fan base and critical praise before they made an impact on the charts with their fourth LP, 2007’s ‘Boxer.’ It marked a gradual shift away from some of their more rustic influences, as they embraced a more expansive, orchestral sound behind the literate lyrics and brooding vocals of frontman Matt Berninger. An album-oriented band that had yet to land on the Hot 100, the National catapulted into the Top 3 of the album charts in multiple countries with 2010’s ‘High Violet.’ They remained a Top 3 act throughout the decade, which included the still more expansive, Grammy-winning ‘Sleep Well Beast,’ from 2017, and 2019’s chart-topping ‘I Am Easy to Find.’ Following a collaboration with Taylor Swift on her 2020 track “Coney Island,” the National contributed to the soundtrack for the 2021 film ‘Cyrano’ and released a one-off single, 2022’s “Weird Goodbyes” with Bon Iver. Their ninth studio album, ‘First Two Pages of Frankenstein,’ will be released by 4AD on April 28, 2023. (Bio: Rovi / Photo: Josh Goleman/4AD/Beggars/Press)

data.title: Bon Iver Essentials
data.description: Over the course of three albums, Bon Iver has gradually evolved from the sparse folk songs from the snowy Wisconsin backwoods, to delicate and epic ballads, to intricate, layered, symbol-laden from a fantastic alternate universe. Always gorgeous, deeply personal and from the idiosyncratic sonic touch of mastermind Justin Vernon, this playlist gathers essential tracks from the universe of Bon Iver. (Photo: Secretly Canadian)

data.title: Mumford & Sons Essentials
data.description: As part of the London underground folk scene, the four-piece outfit built around Marcus Mumford first started to play together in 2007. Inspired by folk and bluegrass, the band played extensively in London and on UK festival circuit before recording and releasing their 2009 'Sigh No More' album debut. The lead single, “Little Lion Man,” was an instant hit and helped pave the way to the global success that Mumford & Sons enjoy today. The band made their triumphant return with 'Babel,' an album that would win the Grammy for Album Of The Year in 2013. (Cover: Mumford & Sons/Photo: Rovi)

data.title: Iron & Wine Essentials
data.description: Iron & Wine has always been about the soft-spoken, bearded singer and songwriter Sam Beam. Born in South Carolina, and graduating from Florida State University Film School, Beam made a living as a professor of film at the University of Miami before being persuaded to record some of the songs he’d been writing for years. Sub Pop took notice of his four-track recordings, and released his debut full length 'The Creek Drank the Cradle' in 2002, earning him comparisons to artists like Nick Drake and Elliot Smith. Beam, however, quickly evolved beyond those initial comparisons, setting out on a journey on his own with more professional sounding albums like 'Our Endless Numbered Days' (2004) and 'The Shepherd’s Dog' (2007), both considered among his finest work and modern day classics. For his later albums, Beam has explored further musical landscapes, including jazz and R&B influences. (Photo: Rovi)

data.title: Sufjan Stevens Essentials
data.description:
Sufjan Stevens (b. 1975, Detroit, MI) has never stuck to a certain musical style for his highly ambitious projects. Since his eclectic debut album ‘A Sun Came’ (2000), Stevens has continued to explore a vast musical landscape, from banjo-folk to orchestrated baroque pop, from lo-fi indie to electronica. The multi-talented artist is widely known for his 2005 album ‘Illinois’ (part of his 50 States album series) and intimate, personal LP ‘Carrie & Lowell’ (2015). This playlist gives you some highlights from one the most cherished pop princes of the 21st century. 

(Cover: Rovi, press)

data.title: Fleetwood Mac Essentials
data.description: Fleetwood Mac was founded as a blues band by Peter Green in 1967 and named after drummer Mick Fleetwood and bassist John McVie. Peter Green left in 1969, and the band has since featured a cast of brilliant talents, most notably Christine McVie, Stevie Nicks and Lindsey Buckingham, who joined the band in the '70s, catapulting Fleetwood Mac into one of the best selling bands of all time. With sales exceeding 100 million records worldwide, and the album 'Rumours' alone selling more than 40 million copies, the legacy of this group cannot be underestimated. Fleetwood Mac was inducted into the Rock & Roll Hall of Fame in 1998. (Photo: Rovi)

data.title: Massive Attack Essentials
data.description: As godfathers of modern dance music—by way of trip-hop—Massive Attack pioneered the pairing of dark and brooding electronica with clear-as-glass vocals for a sound that is a soulful as analogue and sharp as digital. Once a trio, now a duo, few of their peers remain as relevant with the discography to prove it. (Photo: Rovi)

data.title: Lenny Kravitz Essentials
data.description: Lenny Kravitz has made a successful career out of harking back to the music of yesterday -- mingling classic rock, blues, reggae and more to create his own unique style. From his late-'80s debut 'Let Love Rule' to his 2018 release 'Raise Vibration,' Kravitz has spent three decades getting us to groove. (Photo: Rovi)

data.title: Rod Stewart Essentials
data.description: Rod Stewart and his signature raspy voice have since the late ‘60s been a staple of the British rock scene, releasing critically acclaimed albums both as a solo artist and in bands like the Faces and The Jeff Beck Group. (Photo: Rovi)

data.title: Christine and the Queens Essentials
data.description: With her signature blend of catchy pop, electronica, and dance, Christine and the Queens took the French music scene by storm. With her style in a state of constant evolution, Christine doesn't fear to explore music in all its different forms. (Photo: Press / Because Music)

data.title: Joy Division Essentials
data.description: Joy Division was the definitive band of the post-punk era, and a bedrock for any strain of alternative music culture to emerge since its martyred vocalist and lyricist, Ian Curtis, committed suicide in 1980, at age 23. To absorb Joy Division’s essential discography isn’t time-consuming - two studio LPs, ‘Unknown Pleasures’ and ‘Closer,’ plus the epochal singles compilation ‘Substance’ — but in those two and a half hours of music, one can hear the stark conceptual language that made U2, the Cure, Depeche Mode and so many other historic groups possible. Peter Hook, playing robust, direct basslines, made himself the music’s melodic center; guitarist and keyboardist Bernard Sumner summoned up waves of forbidding atmosphere; and drummer Stephen Morris provided just enough minimalist thrust to urge the band onward without distracting from any of its other working parts. As a singer and songwriter, Curtis was Joy Division’s spiritual core, and it was in his unforgiving baritone and lyrics that the band communicated the most integral part of its influence: rock and roll as a way not to rebel or release but as a strategy for morbid self-reflection with no end. (Photo: Rovi)

data.title: The Jacksons Essentials
data.description: With a new label and new name, the Jacksons wasted little time taking the mid-'70s by storm. Hits like "Enjoy Yourself" and "Shake Your Body (Down to the Ground)" established the group, and a collaboration with Mick Jagger, "State of Shock," arose in 1984. (Photo: Rovi)
